1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,345
You can also loop through all the elements of a list using a for loop.

2

00:00:04,345  -->  00:00:07,220
You'll remember for loops from the previous lessons,

3

00:00:07,220  -->  00:00:12,035
and now we get to see this powerful skill we learned in a more data-centric manner.

4

00:00:12,035  -->  00:00:17,600
Using a for loop over a list is like scanning each item in your shopping cart.

5

00:00:17,600  -->  00:00:20,840
Here, we'll see it print out each item in the loop.

6

00:00:20,840  -->  00:00:23,210
Remember our format of for loops.

7

00:00:23,210  -->  00:00:27,880
For tells Python, we want to iterate through a specific item,

8

00:00:27,880  -->  00:00:29,500
which we can name anything.

9

00:00:29,500  -->  00:00:32,300
But here we declare a single item called

10

00:00:32,300  -->  00:00:37,930
fruit in a list of items in a predefined array called fruits.

11

00:00:37,930  -->  00:00:41,770
The output is apple, banana, and cherry.

12

00:00:41,770  -->  00:00:44,950
The for loop automatically goes through each element,

13

00:00:44,950  -->  00:00:46,730
in our case, each fruit,

14

00:00:46,730  -->  00:00:50,050
and prints each item one at a time,

15

00:00:50,050  -->  00:00:53,030
iterating through the fruits array.
